br />Which the vsyscall code really shouldn't have.<br /><br />That said, it might be worth removing the "prefetchw(&amp;mm-&gt;mmap_sem)"<br />from the VM fault path. Partly because software prefetches have never<br />ever worked on any reasonable hardware, and partly because it could<br />seriously screw up things like the vsyscall stuff.<br /><br />I think we only turn prefetchw into an actual prefetch instruction on<br />3DNOW hardware. Which is the *old* AMD chips. I don't think even the<br />Athlon does that.<br /><br />Anyway, it might be interesting to see a instruction-level annotated<br />profile of do_page_fault() or whatever<br /><br />&gt; So with CONFIG_NUMA_BALANCING=y we are taking a higher page<br />&gt; fault rate, in exchange for a speedup.<br /><br />The thing is, so is autonuma.<br /><br />And autonuma doesn't show any of these problems. Autonuma didn't need<br />vsyscall hacks, autonuma didn't need TLB flushing optimizations,<br />autonuma just *worked*, and in fact got big speedups when Mel did the<br />exact same loads on that same machine, presumably with all the same<br />issues..<br /><br />Why are you ignoring that fact?<br /><br />                  Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
